Ammonia release emergency response would be done by the Salinas City Fire Department.  DCC~CDS has coordinated emergency response with the Fire Department including the installation of a Knox Box.  WPS would also be notified in case of a release.  WPS is located about 10 miles from the facility and employs technicians trained beyond 29 CFR 1910.120(q) Awareness level.  The Technician's role would be to support the Fire Department if an ammonia emergency were to occur.  WPS and its Refrigerating technicians maintain control of their written ammonia emergency procedures and equipment. 

1.6   Planned changes to improve safety

The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):

 - Process Hazard Analysis update;
 - Compliance Audits;
 - Mechanical Integrity Program (Routine Inspections & Maintenance);
 - IIAR Bulletin 109 Safety Inspections; 
 - Cal/ARP Seismic Assessment; and
 - DCC~CDS & WPS Inspection Protocols

Each of the Programs above may result in recommendations ranging from capital improvements to routine maintenance of the plant. When appropriate, Service Calls are established in parallel to identified needs. Current planned changes to improve safety include recent PHA 5-Year update recommendations, which include mechanical and administrative improvements. A written record of the recommendations has been prepared and submitted to DCC Management. Completion of changes resulting from the most recent PHA is expected by 2/28/2020, during seasonal shutdown.  

End Executive Summary June 2019
